URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS126316440	2855	species	Black Kite	Milvus migrans			3			United Kingdom	GB	England	GB-ENG	Cornwall	GB-ENG-CON		Porthcurno to Porthgwarra walk	L1275225	P	50.0390379	-5.6651775	2011-09-15	11:40:00		RARE. Flying together. I only saw them distantly, but I was struck by how kite-like they looked, both in their manner of flying and in their profile (long wings, prominently fingered wingtips, long tail). Tail was not forked enough for Red Kite (not that Red Kites are likely in Cornwall either). Still, 3 Black Kites seemed unusual enough that I wasn't confident about an ID. But when I later saw reports online of 3 Black Kites seen flying together in the area at precisely the same time that I'd seen them, I figured that served as sufficient confirmation. Reported here: http://www.cornwall-birding.co.uk/recent-sightings/thursday-15th-september-2011-cornwall-bird-reports-2/ . Later in the week I saw four birders with telescopes come through the grounds although they were not staying at the hotel. The group was guided by Tamba Suso who told us about other guided trips available & afterwards I signed up for Lamin Lodge. Tamba ended up becoming our trusted guide for the whole holiday & not just for birding, he took us out to Senegambia Market as well. However the birding was excellent in the hotel gardens & allowed me to start to feel more comfortable with my own identifications. The walk started at the birdwatching hut that sits in the middle of the hotel's grounds & which always seemed to have a few people in it.--Weather: hot & sunny.		obs288407	Marcus	Hunt	S10639672	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	80	3.219		6	1		1	0

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS101177734	2855	species	Black Kite	Milvus migrans			5			Hong Kong	HK	Hong Kong	HK-				Mai Po Nature Reserve	L1012793	H	22.4953698	114.0488684	2010-11-10	08:00:00	WWF-Hong Kong----A new species of goose for Hong Kong found at Mai Po Nature ReserveNovember 10, 2010-- ----A small flock of geese from two different species, one of which is new to Hong Kong, arrived at the Mai Po Nature Reserve this week. Wild geese seldom visit Hong Kong, and the visiting group of four is the largest number ever to be seen in the territory. The news is causing a buzz in the local birding community.Among the group, 2 individuals are confirmed to be Taiga Bean Goose Anser fabalis middendorffii, which is a new record for Hong Kong. The other species Tundra Bean Goose Anser serrirostris, is the second record locally. It was only previously seen in Hong Kong last year on New Year Day.----The geese are now feeding and roosting daily at the newly refurbished freshwater Pond #8a inside the Reserve. Over the summer we spent 4 months enhancing Pond #8a for waterbirds and the day following its completion the geese moved in, said WWF-Hong Kongs Reserve Manager Bena Smith. The pond contains flooded grassland, a new habitat type for Mai Po, which the geese find very attractive. There is a good chance that they may stay here for the winter.----Smith believes the cold spell of weather at the end of October brought the rare visitors to Hong Kong. In the past 5 years there have only been three goose records from Deep Bay (2005, 2006 and 2009).----The geese were first seen flying over the Reserve on 30 October, then later briefly seen on both the inter-tidal mudflat and Lut Chau fishponds south of Mai Po. They were not re-sighted until November 3rd when a well known young local birdwatcher sat in the Tower Hide overlooking Pond #8a spotted them.----The recent trend of new waterbird species being recorded in the Deep Bay wetlands and increasing waterbird numbers is great news for local birdwatchers and conservationists, said Smith. However to ensure Hong Kongs future generations have opportunity to experience and enjoy wetlands and waterbirds like we do today, it is important to protect the health and integrity of the Deep Bay ecosystem, he added.----Bean Goose''s Profile--Diagnostic Feature: yellow/orange-yellow spot at the tip of the bill, hence its name--Body Colour: Dark brown head and neck contrasting pale grey breast, dark brown wings with white edge on feathers, bright orange legs, black bill--Habitat: Large lakes, pools, marshy wetlands, rivers and streams--Diet: Herbivorous, its diet consisting of herbs, grasses, sedges and mosses--Wintering Ground: Eastern China, Korea and Japan----Taiga Bean Goose--Scientific Name: Anser fabalis middendorffii--Body Length: 90-100cm --Weight: 4.6-5.1kg--Body Feature: slightly larger size with longer and more slender bill.--Breeding Ground: East Transbaikalia, Siberia and Kamchatka----Tundra Bean Goose--Scientific Name: Anser serrirostris--Body Length: 78-89cm--Weight: 2.8-3.2kg--Body Feature: slightly smaller in size, shorter and thicker neck with rounder head and stubbier bill--Breeding Ground: North north-east Siberia and East Chukotka and West Kamchatka------ ------  ---- --------Related LinksVisit Mai Po------------	2 in intimacy 	obs38830	Mike	Fung	S7093384	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD_CAN	480	4		1	1		1	0

This covers east of Hong Kong so I thought it would do the trick.  I did not realize until now that Bean Goose is a rarity there.  Nor did I realize that the species was split.  I was 100% positive I had Bean Goose (but now that it has been a while I am doubting myself), the question is which species.  Had I known this was such a rarity I may have gone back to get photos.  Anyway, the birds were definitely NOT Greater White-fronted Goose.  There was a group of 4 or so, if I remember correctly.  They were relatively large geese, dark brown with yellow bill tips.  I don''t remember having any trouble identifying the birds, as I assumed they were common and they aren''t exactly easily confused with other species (as far as I can tell). It is called La Commenda, and is near the village of Montefiascone and the city of Viterbo in northern Lazio, just south of Umbria and Tuscany. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS156500315	2855	species	Black Kite	Milvus migrans			X			Nepal	NP	Madhyamanchal	NP-1				Sindhupalchok District	L1588241	P	27.9095466	85.6242719	1991-02-23	10:00:00	On foot with Ellen Vor der Bruegge.  On Feb. 23, we hiked up river from the road head at Melamchi to the village of Tipeni, where we spent the nights of Feb. 23-25.  On Feb. 26, we hiked up out of the river valley onto the high ridge where we overnighted at Manekharka.  On Feb. 27, we hiked back down to Tipeni and spent the night.  Then Feb. 28, we hiked down river again to Melamchi.  I don't know the total distance from Melamchi to Manekharka, but given it is an all-day hike to Tipeni and another day to Manekharka, I estimate the distance to be at least 20 miles roundtrip (allowing for how slowly we had to hike uphill and the twists and turns of the path from Tipeni to Manekharka).  From Manekharka we had a fabulous view through the clouds of the peak Gangchenpo (about 22,000 ft. elev.) looming high over us.  We did not have a bird guidebook with us (bought one in Kathmandu immediately after the trip and identified species from memory), but our slow pace on foot allowed for some very good birding.		obs34154	Christopher	Dunford	S10989093	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	1200	32.187		2	1		1	0

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS112035401	2855	species	Black Kite	Milvus migrans			20			Portugal	PT	Beja	PT-02				Castro Verde Plains	L1110420	P	37.781601	-8.0572701	2003-04-22	05:10:00	Morning:  Depart 0535 for Castro Verde plains, with coffee in Castro Verde early at 0615.  Also birding with friends of Meegs: an Irishman named Hugh and PA birder Chris Dooley, both fixtures at Cape May at various times.  ----We started on the road to Mértola from Castro Verde town and turned R onto a dirt track at 37 47.419 N, 08 00.766 W, which is unmarked.  This is the track to what has been the best spot in the Alentejo for Black-bellied Sandgrouse, along with a few other choice birds (100s of both Little and Great Bustards, a large colony of Lesser Kestrels, many larks, local Tawny Pipits).  Right around here later in the day we had our only Red Kite at 37 42.872 N, 07 47.451 W.  We had probably 18 Black-winged Kites (a fair rarity in Europe) all day, plus a nice number of Black Kites despite the rain.  We were forced by deep muddy ruts to turn around, go back to main road, continue east for a bit (R), then turn (R) again at the first real road, marked Penilhos.  Go about a km to a village, then turn (R) again into a small farmstead (sign: M Legur), going past/through it into the same large field.  Then drive straight through the bldgs on the dirt track back to the west, bearing first a bit right at the ruins (kestrels  some 60 nests inside 3 bldgs), then strongly left and downhill to the spot that holds the Black-bellied Sandgrouse.  We found about 7-9 birds here, seen mostly in flight.  The precise spot was 37 42.958 N, 07 53.599 W.  Many of both bustards about, five Stone Curlews, Short-toed and Calandra Larks aplenty, and we probably saw 70 Red-legged Partridge over the course of the day, so just a lot of ground traffic compared to anywhere else Ive been in Europe.  From here, we went on to the ruined (nearly) village of Guerreiro 37 42.958 N, 07 53.599 W, to the south, then arced broadly west of it, returning to the main road (123) at 37 42.258 N, 7 56.333 W (check this!) where a Whimbrel turned up in the wet field, and headed back east, crossing the N122 (which leads south to Mértola) and followed signs (mostly!) north and east to Pulo do Lobo gorge, a great spot.  Probably should have tried for a few warblers here, but cool and rainy/windy still.  Blue Rock Thrush and Rock Bunting were at the gorge itself, easily, but no vultures or Black Stork, of course.  Great Spotted Cuckoo was fine in the rougher patch of the entrance road, our only one of the day, along with a close Hoopoe.  On the drive, countless White Stork nests (full of Spanish Sparrows), abundant Corn Buntings, hundreds of Spotless Starlings, etc.  Not as many raptors as in a normal year, esp. of the eagles, according to McClintock.  ----The afternoon route was not carefully plotted, as it became clear that local knowledge of road conditions (in rains), location of certain cereal crops (for bustards, etc.), vernal ponds (etc.) would be required to do the area any justice.  The year 2003 had been unusual in being cold and rainy, and the route we were doing was quite different from the norm.  So it occurred to me at this point that wed need Frank along for at least a few years to get the real lay of the land (hes sort of the Ken de Smet of the area, eh).  The richness of this area in birdlife, though, makes some of the birds really easy, so even a bad day here would seem incredibly good.  ----We had lunch at an old ruined church with Bee-eaters around it, at 37 44.757 N, 07 53.221 W. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS120849992	2866	issf	Black Kite	Milvus migrans	Black Kite (Yellow-billed)	Milvus migrans aegyptius/parasitus	X			Ethiopia	ET	Oromia	ET-OR				Ethiopia Oromia Addis Ababa to Awash NP	L1191719	P	8.619041	39.3585205	2011-05-29	08:00:00	Sites seen and towns passed through included: Lake Hora at Debre Zeit/Bisoftu; Mojo where one would turn south if going to Rift Valley Lakes or Kenya; Nazret/Adama; Korke, humble village on a high ridge in site of volcano Fentale, with Orthodow church on one side of highway and mosque on the other side;  Lake Metahara, a toxic lake not draining to the Awash River and rising over the highway and railroad so requiring relocation of road and railroad, and Awash Falls in Awash National Park. Since losing Eritrea, Ethiopia must traffic through that country to reach the Red Sea at Aseb on the Red Sea, and must traffic through Djibouti to reach the sea between the Red Sea and the Gulf of Aden. Traffic with the sea also occurs through the port of Mombasa, Kenya.  Ethiopia never colonized, but has had some pressures from the west at times, such as the Italian occupation during WWII. Also, there was 17 years of communist rule, after Haile Selassie was deposed. The country is on the Julian calendar, and so is now 7 years behind the Gregorian calendar?  Saw Beisa Oryx and Sommering''s Gazelles at Awash NP.  Also saw warthogs and a large tortoise.  Spent the night at Awash Falls Lodge, sounding the roar of the Awash River starting it''s spill into a deep gorge downstream. In Oromia Region it is the start of rainy season, so the Awash River at the NP is muddy, and across Oromia the fields were being turned by 2-ox teams. After 3 days or more in Ethiopia we was our first tractor, which was turning the fields at the Kuyere Adventist College founded by a Toppenberg about 60 years ago.  Even the paved roads, which are few, swarm with goats, donkeys, horses, cattle, dogs, and people. The only fences are in the immediate vicinity of tiny villages or single huts.  Children and women herd the cattle, trying to get them off the road when motor traffic passes.  Matatus are 3-wheeled tiny tiny blue and white taxis.  Wild and primitive markets scenes. Dirt yards are swept with twig/branch brooms.		obs235854	Sam	Harboldt	S8401692	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	600	207.605		3	1		1	0

King Tedros, beloved ruler of Ethiopia, asked Queen Victoria for help in quelling raids from Sudan.  She wouldn''t help.  In time Tedros son, the Prince, was taken prisoner and was raised in England.  We saw people by the roadside with the leafy boughs of peppertree - understand that it is used to repel flies. Gas equivalent to about $1.00 per liter in Ethiopia - now is about $3.60 per gallon in Jackson, so apparently not a great difference. We saw it both on the way to the nets and on the way back to the hostel from the nets.  It was amazingly close. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS93982653	2866	issf	Black Kite	Milvus migrans	Black Kite (Yellow-billed)	Milvus migrans aegyptius/parasitus	4			Tanzania	TZ	Arusha	TZ-01				Ngorongoro Crater	L930127	P	-3.2145598	35.4721069	2009-02-09	06:30:00	Game drive from Ngorongoro Sopa Lodge into the Crater.  Keith and I were with Martin Plant; Peter was driving.  A few nightjars flew up from the road at the start of the drive.  Abdim''s Storks were in the grass, White Storks (including some sandy-colored juvs) in the grass and in trees.  Five or six Yellow Wagtails were in the road when two jackals were going after (unsuccessfully!) a newborn wildebeest.  I saw Yellow Wagtails (that''s what Zimmerman calls them)  in the grass a couple more times after that.  I have entered them as Western Yellow Wagtails.  At 8:10 AM, Keith got an i.d. shot of what looks to me like M. f. flava, adult male, winter (Zimmerman, Plate 69, gray crown, dark face, a little white above eye, below eye, and between eye and bill, yellow throat) in the grass.  At 9:48 AM, I got an i.d. shot of what looks like M. f. lutea, yellow-headed male, spring (Zimmerman, Plate 69, yellow head and underparts) in the grass.  I believe that M. f. flava and M. f. lutea are both subspecies of Western Yellow Wagtail; I hope that''s correct.----We saw 8 Ostriches together before we got to the hippo pool.  At the hippo pool (the beautiful one that is not the picnic spot), I saw a Common Moorhen, 3 Cattle Egrets, a Little Egret (identified by Martin, like our Snowy Egret with yellow slippers), a Gray Heron, a Squacco Heron in breeding plumage, Blacksmith Plovers, and in the reeds 3 Fan-tailed Widowbirds (female, brown-streaked, orange on wings).----Keith got photos of a Rosy-throated (Zimmerman: Rosy-breasted) Longclaw, a Rufous-naped Lark, and an i.d. shot of a Fischer''s Sparrow Lark.  Red-capped Lark (top of head chestnut) was in grass, too far away for a photo.----Two Cape Teal and a Hamerkop were in the water.  There were lots of Lesser Flamingos at the lake, but the road to the lake was cordoned off.  (John Bryant, the South African, told us that in the past, that road was open to vehicles.)  Five Spur-winged Geese, 6 Gray Crowned Cranes, and 3 Ostriches (one posed) were in the grass.  Awhile later I saw 8 Gray Crowned Cranes at one time, 5 in one tree, 3 in another.  Keith got an i.d. shot of a bird that turned out to be a breeding male Yellow Bishop in a bush along the road.----At the picnic spot with a hippo pool, there were a few Superb Starlings, Rufous-tailed Weavers (and trees with their nests), and Vitelline Masked Weavers (red eye) building nests.  A male Speke''s Weaver (yellow eye) landed on our table while we were eating lunch.  There was a flock of Fan-tailed Widowbirds (mostly female/juv, Keith managed to get a photo of one male in breeding plumage).  Six coots and a few moorhens were in the water.  The Pied Kingfisher was hovering over the water.  The African Jacana was with the Blacksmith Plovers.  All the photographers got flight shots of three Black (Yellow-billed) Kites.  There was much discussion about which name was preferred, but it looks like either name works!----On our way back to the lodge, we saw a Little Bee-eater on a spike of grass and a Black Kite flying almost to the top of the Crater.     		obs40982	Sharon	Kennedy	S6541024	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	390	8.047		4	1		1	0

I had wanted our Uganda trip to do something off the ''regular'' tourist route, so I planned a day to look for Fox''s Weaver, Uganda''s only endemic. We left Jinja at 6:30 a.m. for the 4 hour drive here (on good roads). We then got into a small dugout canoe with boatman to paddle us through the lily-pads to the "known" weaver colony on a island in middle of west end of lake. Lovely day and beautiful spot. But we learned in 2011 that the weavers we saw and photo'd here were N. Brown-throated Weaver, not Fox's -- as it turns out, no one quite knows where Fox's nests.		obs167174	Rita	Carratello	S7259850	eBird - Traveling  Count	EBIRD	90	3.219		5	1	G210830	1	0
